      "stem": "A small bakery sells cookies for \\$5 each. The bakery is open every morning, and on a typical day demand exceeds capacity. The marginal cost of producing the $n$-th cookie on a given day is $MC(n) = 1 + 0.50 n$ dollars (small $n$ early in the day when ingredients are fresh and staff is rested; larger $n$ later in the day when ingredients are depleted and staff is tiring). 1. Compute the marginal cost of the 4th cookie and the marginal cost of the 9th cookie produced that day.\n2. For each of those two cookies, state in one short sentence whether the bakery should produce that cookie, and why.\n3. How many cookies in total should the bakery produce that day? Show how you arrived at the answer using marginal reasoning.",
      "model_answer": "1. $MC(4) = 1 + 0.50 \\times 4 = 3$ dollars. $MC(9) = 1 + 0.50 \\times 9 = 5.50$ dollars. 2. The 4th cookie: produce. Marginal benefit (\\$5) is greater than marginal cost (\\$3), so the cookie adds \\$2 to profit. The 9th cookie: don't produce. Marginal benefit (\\$5) is less than marginal cost (\\$5.50), so the cookie subtracts \\$0.50 from profit. 3. The bakery should produce cookies as long as $MC(n) \\leq 5$. Solving \\$1 + 0.50 n \\leq 5$ gives \\$0.50 n \\leq 4$, so $n \\leq 8$. Check: $MC(8) = 1 + 0.50 \\times 8 = 5$ (exactly breakeven, produce); $MC(9) = 5.50 > 5$ (don't produce). The bakery should produce 8 cookies.",
