      "stem": "At a press conference, a senator says: 'A \\$15 federal minimum wage would reduce poverty, and we should pass it because reducing income inequality is the right thing to do.' 1. Identify the positive claim and the normative claim in this statement.\n2. The senator's prediction in the positive claim holds 'all else equal.' Name one realistic factor that, if it changed at the same time as the wage increase, could prevent poverty from falling as the senator predicts.\n3. Describe one concrete piece of evidence that would help test the senator's positive claim. Be specific about what data or study design you would want.",
      "model_answer": "1. Positive claim: 'A \\$15 federal minimum wage would reduce poverty.' This is a predictive claim about an effect of policy; it is in principle testable against evidence. Normative claim: 'We should pass it because reducing income inequality is the right thing to do.' This rests on a value judgment that reducing inequality is good. 2. Many acceptable answers: a recession that reduces employer demand for low-wage labor while the wage floor rises (so workers laid off lose income); employers raising consumer prices broadly so low-wage workers' real wages don't rise; a large shift in low-wage work from formal to informal employment (cash, off-the-books) that doesn't pay the \\$15 minimum. 3. A natural experiment comparing states that raised their minimum wage to \\$15 to similar states that didn't, tracking poverty-rate changes over a 2-3 year window while controlling for local economic conditions. A panel study tracking individual workers whose wages were raised by the policy and whether they crossed above the poverty line also works.",
