      "stem": "Read Leonard Read's essay [*I, Pencil*](https://fee.org/articles/i-pencil/), about 1,800 words. Then write a roughly 250-word multi-part response covering the three parts below. Label each part 1 / 2 / 3. Cite specifics from the essay where useful. 1. Identify three distinct resources that are scarce in the economic sense in the supply chain of making a pencil. For each, name an opportunity cost: what could that resource have been used for instead?\n2. Write one positive claim and one normative claim that the essay either makes explicitly or implies. In one sentence, state how you can tell them apart.\n3. The essay's central observation is that no single person knows how to make a pencil from scratch, yet pencils get made. In 2-3 sentences, state what economic concept from this unit best names how that coordination happens, and explain how that concept fits the essay's story.",
      "model_answer": "1. Cedar wood (opportunity cost: building materials, furniture, other pencils). Graphite (opportunity cost: industrial lubricants, batteries, art supplies). Skilled labor (opportunity cost: any other work the loggers, miners, and assembly workers could have been doing). 2. Positive claim: any factual statement about how pencils are made or what countries source the inputs, for example, that the cedar comes from Northern California and Oregon. Normative claim: Read's framing that the spontaneous-order coordination is good, that the lack of central control is praiseworthy. The positive claim can be checked against records; the normative depends on a value judgment. 3. The concept is opportunity cost, applied at every link of the chain: each actor (logger, miner, factory worker, retailer) weighs what she gives up to do this work versus the best alternative she could be doing. The essay's story works because at every step, the actor is doing the work whose opportunity cost is acceptable given the price she receives. No one needs a master plan because each actor's opportunity-cost comparison, made locally, adds up.",
