      "mode": "short",
      "tags": [
        "U6",
        "CLO-1"
      ],
      "stem": "For each of the following per-unit excise taxes, predict which side of the market (buyers or sellers) bears the larger share of the tax. Give your reasoning in one sentence per item, using the intuition that the side which can more easily walk away from the market bears less of the tax. 1. A \\$0.50 per-gallon tax on gasoline at the only gas station in a remote rural town.\n2. A \\$0.50 per-pound tax on one specific brand of premium ground beef sold in a city with many beef brands.\n3. A \\$20 per-ticket tax on lifesaving medication that has no substitute.\n4. A \\$1,000 per-yacht tax on luxury yachts costing over \\$100,000.",
      "model_answer": "1. Buyers bear most of the tax. Demand is inelastic (the only gas station nearby; few substitutes), so buyers are 'stuck' and cannot easily avoid the tax. 2. Sellers of the premium brand bear most. Demand is elastic (many brand substitutes), so buyers easily switch and the brand can't pass the tax through. 3. Buyers bear nearly all of the tax. Demand is highly inelastic (no substitute for the medication), so buyers are stuck. 4. Sellers (and ultimately the boat-building industry workers) bear most. Demand for luxury yachts is highly elastic (the wealthy can substitute to other forms of spending), which is exactly the lesson of the 1990 yacht-tax case from the Required Resources.",
      "key_points": [
        "1: buyers stuck (inelastic)",
        "2: sellers stuck (elastic demand for brand)",
        "3: buyers stuck (inelastic)",
        "4: sellers stuck (elastic demand for luxury); echoes 1990 yacht-tax case"
      ],
      "grading_notes": "1.5 per scenario correctly classified WITH a one-sentence reason that names elasticity and identifies whether buyers or sellers can 'walk away.' Classification alone earns 0.5.",
      "review": [
        {
          "label": "OpenStax Ch 3.4, 4.3: surplus, price controls, and taxation",
          "url": "https://openstax.org/books/principles-microeconomics-3e/pages/1-introduction"
        },
        {
          "label": "MRU \u2014 Principles of Microeconomics",
          "url": "https://mru.org/principles-economics-microeconomics"
        }
      ]
