      "stem": "The wholesale price of cocoa beans rises sharply because of a poor harvest in West Africa. Holding everything else equal, what happens to the supply curve for chocolate bars?",
      "options": [
        {
          "letter": "A",
          "text": "It does not shift; quantity supplied falls along the existing curve.",
          "comment": "The price of chocolate itself did not change in the stem. A non-price variable did, so the curve shifts."
        },
        {
          "letter": "B",
          "text": "It shifts right, because chocolate makers will produce more to cover their costs.",
          "comment": "A common student error. Higher costs reduce supply, not raise it."
        },
        {
          "letter": "C",
          "text": "It shifts left, because chocolate makers face higher input costs.",
          "comment": "Correct. Higher input costs reduce the quantity supplied at every price; the curve shifts left."
        },
        {
          "letter": "D",
          "text": "It shifts left, because demand for chocolate has fallen.",
          "comment": "No demand variable changed in the stem."
        }
      ],
      "answer": "C",
