      "stem": "When a per-unit tax reduces the quantity transacted in a market, the deadweight loss is best described as:",
      "options": [
        {
          "letter": "A",
          "text": "The total tax revenue the government collects on the new traded quantity.",
          "comment": "Revenue is a transfer, not a loss. DWL is the lost value of trades that no longer happen."
        },
        {
          "letter": "B",
          "text": "The lost value of trades that would have created surplus but no longer occur.",
          "comment": "Correct. DWL is the value of trades the tax squeezes out."
        },
        {
          "letter": "C",
          "text": "The combined drop in consumer surplus and producer surplus, including the transfer to the government.",
          "comment": "The transfer to the government is not part of DWL; only the value that vanishes entirely is."
        },
        {
          "letter": "D",
          "text": "The cost the government incurs to administer and enforce the new tax.",
          "comment": "Administrative cost is a separate concept from DWL."
        }
      ],
      "answer": "B",
