      "mode": "short",
      "tags": [
        "U6",
        "CLO-6"
      ],
      "stem": "A state proposes a new $\\$1.20$ per-pack excise tax on cigarettes. Before the tax, the equilibrium price is $\\$8.00$ per pack and equilibrium quantity is 50 million packs per year. The state economist estimates $|E_d| = 0.4$ (demand for cigarettes is inelastic) and $E_s = 1.6$ (supply is fairly elastic). Address all four parts. Number your responses. 1. Compute the share of the tax borne by buyers and the share borne by sellers using the formula $\\text{buyer share} = E_s / (E_s + |E_d|)$.\n2. Translate the shares into dollar amounts: how much does the price paid by buyers rise, and how much does the price received by sellers fall?\n3. The legislator pushing the tax says: \"We are taxing the tobacco companies, not the smokers.\" Evaluate this claim in two sentences using your answer to Part 1.\n4. Suppose the state instead proposes the same tax on chewing tobacco, which has $|E_d| = 1.5$ and $E_s = 1.6$. Without recomputing exact amounts, predict whether the buyer share, the total revenue raised per dollar of tax, and the deadweight loss per dollar of tax would each be higher, lower, or about the same than for cigarettes. Justify each in one sentence.",
      "model_answer": "Buyer share 80%, seller share 20%. Buyers absorb \\$0.96 of the \\$1.20; sellers absorb \\$0.24. Legislator confuses statutory and economic incidence. For chewing tobacco: buyer share lower, revenue lower, DWL higher.",
      "key_points": [
        "Correctly applies buyer-share formula to get 80%",
        "Translates shares into dollar amounts (\\$0.96 / \\$0.24)",
        "Distinguishes statutory from economic incidence",
        "Predicts elasticity comparative-statics for chewing tobacco (3 directions)"
      ],
      "grading_notes": "(tier demoted from LA\u2192SA 2026-05-20 to reduce PS load; Bloom stays analyze so LD-PIL-21B remains satisfied). Original 15-pt rubric: for correct share computation. for the dollar translation. for the legislator critique that names statutory vs economic incidence. for the three chewing-tobacco predictions with one-sentence justifications.",
      "review": [
        {
          "label": "OpenStax Ch 3.4, 4.3: surplus, price controls, and taxation",
          "url": "https://openstax.org/books/principles-microeconomics-3e/pages/1-introduction"
        },
        {
          "label": "MRU \u2014 Principles of Microeconomics",
          "url": "https://mru.org/principles-economics-microeconomics"
        }
      ]
