      "stem": "A financial crisis hits a major city. Unemployment rises and average household incomes fall. Avocados are a normal good. Which of the following best describes the effect on the demand for avocados?",
      "options": [
        {
          "letter": "A",
          "text": "The price of avocados falls because producers lower prices.",
          "comment": "Incorrect. The demand curve shifts; producer pricing reflects supply, not demand."
        },
        {
          "letter": "B",
          "text": "Quantity demanded of avocados falls because the price of avocados rose.",
          "comment": "Incorrect. The scenario does not mention a price change for avocados. A price change causes movement along the curve, not a shift."
        },
        {
          "letter": "C",
          "text": "The demand curve for avocados shifts right as buyers seek cheaper substitutes.",
          "comment": "Incorrect. Shifting toward cheaper substitutes would also reduce avocado demand, but the mechanism stated is wrong: the primary effect here is income, not substitute-seeking."
        },
        {
          "letter": "D",
          "text": "The demand curve for avocados shifts left because buyers now have less income.",
          "comment": "Correct. Income is a demand shifter. For a normal good, lower income reduces demand at every price, shifting the curve left."
        }
      ],
      "answer": "D",
      "solution": "A fall in income reduces demand for a normal good at every price, shifting the entire demand curve leftward. Income is a non-price demand shifter.",
