      "tags": [
        "U8",
        "CLO-6"
      ],
      "stem": "A pizza restaurant in Austin can bake 200 pizzas per week at its current price of \\$12 each. A nearby stadium concert brings a price spike to \\$15 per pizza; the restaurant hustles and produces 260 pizzas that week. Compute the price elasticity of supply using the simple percent-change formula. Round to two decimal places. Step 1: Compute the percent change in quantity supplied.\nStep 2: Compute the percent change in price.\nStep 3: Divide the results.",
      "answer": "1.2",
      "accept": [
        "1.2"
      ],
      "solution": "Step 1: %\u0394Qs = (260 - 200) / 200 \u00d7 100% = 60/200 \u00d7 100% = 30%.\nStep 2: %\u0394P = (15 - 12) / 12 \u00d7 100% = 3/12 \u00d7 100% = 25%.\nStep 3: Es = 30% / 25% = 1.2.\nSupply is elastic (Es > 1). Pizza production can expand quickly (same kitchen, longer hours, same inputs), so supply is elastic in the short run.",
      "review": [
        {
          "label": "OpenStax Ch 5: elasticity",
          "url": "https://openstax.org/books/principles-microeconomics-3e/pages/1-introduction"
        },
        {
          "label": "MRU \u2014 Principles of Microeconomics",
          "url": "https://mru.org/principles-economics-microeconomics"
        }
      ]
