      "mode": "long",
      "tags": [
        "U8",
        "CLO-6"
      ],
      "stem": "**Reading:** The following passage is adapted from OpenStax *Principles of Microeconomics 3e*, Section 5.3. --- A band on tour is playing in an indoor arena with 15,000 seats. The band keeps all revenue from ticket sales. Costs for travel and stage setup are fixed regardless of attendance. All tickets are the same price. The band faces a downward-sloping demand curve: raising the ticket price will sell fewer seats. The central question is how to set price to maximize total revenue. If demand is **elastic** at the current price level, cutting price raises total revenue: the percentage gain in quantity sold exceeds the percentage price drop. If demand is **inelastic** at the current price level, raising price increases total revenue: the percentage price gain exceeds the percentage quantity lost. If demand is **unitary elastic**, revenue is unchanged by a small price movement in either direction. --- **Questions:** **a)** A band currently charges \\$80 per ticket and sells 12,000 of 15,000 available seats. When they test a \\$72 ticket price for a single show, sales rise to 13,200 seats. Using the simple percent-change formula, compute the price elasticity of demand. Is demand elastic, inelastic, or unitary elastic at this price point? **b)** Based on your calculation, should the band lower or raise its ticket price to maximize total revenue? Show whether total revenue actually increases or decreases at the two price points (\\$80 and \\$72) to verify your answer. **c)** Suppose after the price cut, the band sells out all 15,000 seats at \\$70. At that point, the band cannot lower prices further (the venue is full). They are considering moving to a 20,000-seat arena at an added cost of \\$50,000 per show. Explain the economic reasoning the band should use to evaluate this decision, connecting it to the concept of elasticity and the revenue-maximizing price. **d)** A cultural critic argues that bands who charge below maximum willingness-to-pay are acting generously toward fans. An economist observes that below-maximum pricing can be a strategic choice with commercial benefits. Identify one specific commercial benefit the economist might have in mind and explain the economic logic.",
      "model_answer": "A strong answer covers: a) %\u0394Qd = (13,200 - 12,000) / 12,000 \u00d7 100% = +10%.\n%\u0394P = (72 - 80) / 80 \u00d7 100% = -10%.; E; =; +10% / -10%; = 1.0.\nDemand is unitary elastic at this price point. A 10% price cut produces exactly a 10% gain in quantity. b) With unitary elasticity, total revenue is essentially unchanged. Verify:\nTR at \\$80: 80 \u00d7 12,000 = \\$960,000.\nTR at \\$72: 72 \u00d7 13,200 = \\$950,400.\nThe small difference reflects the approximation in the simple percent-change method. At near-unitary elasticity, neither a price cut nor a price increase will meaningfully raise total revenue. c) At 15,000 seats, the venue capacity is the binding constraint. To evaluate the larger arena, the band needs to know whether demand is elastic below the current \\$70 price: could they sell the additional 5,000 seats by cutting price, and would that raise revenue? If demand is elastic below \\$70, moving to a bigger arena and cutting price would raise revenue. The \\$50,000 added cost must be offset by the incremental revenue gain from the additional seats. Elasticity tells the band whether a further price cut generates more revenue (elastic) or less (inelastic). d) One commercial benefit: fans who pay below maximum willingness-to-pay feel positively about the band and spend more on merchandise, recordings, and future concerts. If concert tickets and merchandise are complements (used together at the event), a lower ticket price increases the number of fans attending and therefore increases the quantity of merchandise sold. Total revenue across all revenue streams may be higher at a below-maximum ticket price than at the concert-revenue-only maximum..",
      "key_points": [
        "E",
        "= 1.0 computed correctly (unitary elastic at this price)",
        "Unitary elastic: revenue unchanged by price movement (verified with TR calculation)",
        "Arena decision: evaluate whether demand is elastic below \\$70; compare incremental revenue to \\$50,000 added cost",
        "Commercial benefit: complementary revenue (merchandise, future shows) from below-max pricing"
      ],
      "grading_notes": "for part (a): correct |E| calculation and classification. for part (b): correct revenue rule application and TR verification. for part (c): identifies capacity constraint, correctly invokes elasticity below current price, connects to marginal revenue vs marginal cost logic. for part (d): identifies a specific commercial benefit with correct economic reasoning. Deduct if student conflates slope with elasticity.",
      "review": [
        {
          "label": "OpenStax Ch 5: elasticity",
          "url": "https://openstax.org/books/principles-microeconomics-3e/pages/1-introduction"
        },
        {
          "label": "MRU \u2014 Principles of Microeconomics",
          "url": "https://mru.org/principles-economics-microeconomics"
        }
      ]
